{
  "text": "Proof. Without loss of generality suppose that L \u2286 2 * is a prefix context-free language. There exists a grammar G in weak GNF of height n generating L. When L is scattered, then the claim holds by [CITATION_1] . So suppose that L is quasidense. Then L can be represented as a dense sum of nonempty scattered linear orderings. This means that L can be partitioned into nonempty scattered intervals L i indexed by the elements i of a dense countable linear ordering (D, <) such that if i < j in D then u < s v holds for all u \u2208 L i and v \u2208 L j . By the previous Corollary and clause (3) of Proposition 2.1, FC(L i ) \u2264 \u03c9 n + 1 for each i. Thus, FC(L) \u2264 \u03c9 n + 1.",
